# MOOP — per-site Apache config for a NEW deployment.  TEMPLATE.
# Apache equivalent of docs/nginx/moop-site.conf.example; keep the two in step.
#
# ⚠  SYNTAX verified, BEHAVIOUR not. `httpd -t` accepts this file (checked 2026-07-22 with
#    mod_rewrite loaded), so it will not break an Apache that loads it. But no Apache host
#    has ever SERVED MOOP, so nobody has confirmed the rewrite actually puts the gateway in
#    front of JBrowse. Syntax-OK is not the same as working — a rewrite that silently never
#    fires is exactly the failure this file warns about. Run the VERIFY steps below before
#    trusting it, and please report corrections. Same standing caveat as
#    docs/apache/moop-security.conf.
#
# ⚠  FOR A NEW SITE ONLY. Do not deploy this for a site that already has the auth-gateway
#    rewrite configured (in a <VirtualHost>, an existing conf.d file, or an .htaccess).
#    Two rewrites for the same URL are at best redundant and at worst a redirect loop.
#    Check first:
#
#        grep -rn 'jbrowse2/index.html' /etc/httpd/conf* /etc/apache2 2>/dev/null
#
#    If your new site's prefix comes back, it is already configured — use that, not both.
#
# ── WHAT A SECOND MOOP ACTUALLY NEEDS ───────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Less than you would expect. Where MOOP is a SUBDIRECTORY of the document root
# (DocumentRoot /var/www/html, app at /var/www/html/<site>), Apache already serves and
# executes PHP beneath it. A second deployment at /var/www/html/cuttingclass is SERVED
# THE MOMENT THE FILES EXIST: no new VirtualHost, no ServerName change, no TLS work.
#
# Exactly two things are per-site:
#     1. the JBrowse2 auth-gateway rewrite  ← this file
#     2. the no-exec guard                  ← docs/apache/moop-security.conf, deployed
#                                             separately under a per-site filename
#
# ── SETUP ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   Replace <site> with your site directory name (what config/site_config.php derives
#   from the install path — "cuttingclass" for /var/www/html/cuttingclass).
#
#   1. This file:
#        sed 's#<site>#cuttingclass#g' docs/apache/moop-site.conf.example > /tmp/cc-site.conf
#      RHEL/CentOS/Rocky:
#        sudo cp /tmp/cc-site.conf /etc/httpd/conf.d/cuttingclass-site.conf
#        sudo apachectl configtest && sudo systemctl reload httpd
#      Debian/Ubuntu:
#        sudo cp /tmp/cc-site.conf /etc/apache2/conf-available/cuttingclass-site.conf
#        sudo a2enconf cuttingclass-site && sudo apachectl configtest \
#          && sudo systemctl reload apache2
#
#   2. The guard, the same way, from docs/apache/moop-security.conf with its /moop/ and
#      /var/www/html/moop paths adjusted — see that file's header.
#
#   3. mod_rewrite must be enabled, or the rewrite below silently does nothing and the
#      gateway is bypassed with no error anywhere:
#        RHEL:    ensure `LoadModule rewrite_module modules/mod_rewrite.so` is present
#        Debian:  sudo a2enmod rewrite && sudo systemctl reload apache2
#      Confirm with: apachectl -M | grep rewrite
#
#   Use PER-SITE FILENAMES. Deploying a second site's rules as moop-security.conf
#   overwrites the first site's guard and leaves BOTH protected by only one of them.

# ── JBrowse2 auth gateway (REQUIRED — this is an access control, not a nicety) ───────
#
# JBrowse2 is a static JavaScript app: without this rewrite Apache serves its index.html
# straight from disk and MOOP never sees the request. The session is never checked, so
# NON-PUBLIC ASSEMBLIES ARE EXPOSED to anyone who knows the URL. auth_gateway.php checks
# the session, and for a non-public assembly sends an unauthenticated visitor to log in
# and returns them to the JBrowse URL they asked for.
#
# Anchored to index.html exactly: the rest of the JBrowse app (its JS, CSS and workers,
# served from the same directory) must keep loading normally.
# QSA preserves the ?config=...&organism=...&assembly=... query the gateway reads to
# decide whether the requested assembly is public.

RewriteEngine On
RewriteRule ^/<site>/jbrowse2/index\.html$ /<site>/auth_gateway.php [L,QSA]

# If the rule above does not fire, your Apache is likely matching per-directory (inside a
# <Directory> or .htaccess), where the leading /<site> prefix is stripped. In that context
# use the relative form instead — NOT both:
#
#   <Directory "/var/www/html/<site>/jbrowse2">
#       RewriteEngine On
#       RewriteRule ^index\.html$ /<site>/auth_gateway.php [L,QSA]
#   </Directory>

# ── VERIFY (do this — a 404 or a redirect is not proof of anything) ──────────────────
#
#   Gateway is in front of JBrowse:  logged OUT, in a private window, open
#       http://YOUR-HOST/<site>/jbrowse2/index.html?config=...&organism=X&assembly=Y
#     naming a NON-PUBLIC assembly. You must land on the login page. Being shown the
#     browser means the rewrite never fired — check `apachectl -M | grep rewrite` first,
#     since a missing mod_rewrite fails silently.
#
#   The rest of JBrowse still loads:  a logged-in user opens the same browser and sees
#     tracks. A blank app means the rule is matching more than index.html.
#
#   The guard is the OTHER file's job. Test it with a real .php that would execute, plus a
#   control copy in a normal location; a 404 can just mean the web user cannot read the
#   file. See the VERIFY block in docs/apache/moop-security.conf.
